<strong>Food Reconstruction Project</strong>

Over the past year several CAP graduate fellows worked to recreate an 1860s meal on campus based on archaeological, archival, and historic cookbook research.  Although only photos will be used, check out this short video to learn more:

https://youtu.be/GA73FxdcLio

<strong>2017 Field School</strong>

From May 30th - June 30th MSU Anthropology undergraduate students returned to the site of <a href="http://campusarch.msu.edu/?p=4255">Station Terrace</a> (first located during the summer of 2016) to examine more of the building.  It was a small group this year, but we were able to <a href="http://campusarch.msu.edu/?p=5401">excavate six units</a>, and reveal more of the building's interior and exterior.

[caption id="attachment_26840" align="alignleft" width="273"]<img class="wp-image-26840" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Screen-Shot-2017-07-25-at-4.13.11-PM.png" alt="CAP field school students Josh Eads and Kaleigh Perry excavate underneath ceramic pipes running along the stone foundation." width="273" height="201" /> CAP field school students Josh Eads and Kaleigh Perry excavate underneath ceramic pipes running along the stone foundation.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_26841" align="alignright" width="284"]<img class=" wp-image-26841" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Screen-Shot-2017-07-25-at-4.15.38-PM.png" alt="Unit A north wall stratigraphy. The 2016 test pit is visible on the left side, with undisturbed layers including a feature visible on the right. " width="284" height="211" /> Unit A north wall stratigraphy. The 2016 test pit is visible on the left side, with undisturbed layers including a feature visible on the right.[/caption]

